{{redirect|Kele}}
'''''Kélé''''' is an [[Afro-Saint Lucian]] religion, originated from the [[Djiné]] people of the [[Babonneau]] region. Its primary deities are [[Ogoun|Ogun]], [[Shango]] and [[Eshu]]. ''Kélé'' ceremonies include the drumming of the ''tanbou manman'' (''mother drum'') and the ''tanbou ich'' (''child drum'') of the [[Batá drum]] family.
The religion has its origins in African slaves of the [[Babonneau]] region. The religion is strongly connected to the [[Ogun]] festival in Nigeria. Repressed by the Roman Catholic church until the early 1960s, it had been practiced in secrecy underground. The ritual includes the display of smooth stones (one of Shango's worship items) and iron/steel items in honor of Ogun.<ref>https://books.google.ca/books?id=uspTNzJ_NoYC&pg=PA381&lpg=PA381&dq=st+lucia+kele&source=bl&ots=tPoEjsH0Nc&sig=-Zu4nPy9eZGO8ohv4Gpcb-7Uu6Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBpeqa08_JAhWOoYMKHfucDZUQ6AEILjAD#v=onepage&q=st%20lucia%20kele&f=false</ref> The faith itself is believed to be a Saint Lucian version of [[Yoruba religion]].<ref name="Holloway2005">{{cite book|author=Joseph E. Holloway|title=Africanisms in American Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TmzTyI5rfDMC&pg=PA254|year=2005|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-21749-0|pages=254–}}</ref>

